Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 40th Weekly Dose of Optimism. This Oct=
ober paper, which made the rounds earlier this week [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/7470b67c-df26-4b66-9b29-3c788717463b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], is why we write the Weekly Dose.
Full slate this week, and if you=E2=80=99ll allow us, a bit of shameless (b=
ut hopefully helpful) self-promotion. So throw on some tunes=E2=80=A6=20
And let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by... Composer [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/ca740dbc-085b-4f55-a709-598086107fdc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
You know Composer. I love Composer =E2=80=94 the investing app that helps y=
ou achieve superior returns with logic, data, and now AI integrations. Sinc=
e founding its algorithmic trading platform in 2020, Composer has helped ov=
er 20,000 customers trade 100s of millions of dollars. I=E2=80=99m one of t=
hem =E2=80=94 my Composer portfolio is actually up since I started using it=
 last year, which is incredible because the portfolio of individual stocks =
I own is =E2=80=A6 not.
And Composer [ https://substack.com/redirect/d1b6c6ad-b699-4f9d-accf-a145c3=
7f364d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 is now integrated with ChatGPT-4 and ships new features seemingly every we=
ek. Two features to call to your attention (the video above explains it eve=
n better)
Composer =E2=80=94> ChatGPT: easily copy+paste Composer symphonies into Cha=
tGPT and get plain language explanations of the sophisticated trading logic=
 powering your trading strategies.
NEW: ChatGPT=E2=80=94> Composer: modify trading strategies in ChatGPT, copy=
+paste code back into Composer, and your symphony is automatically updated.
Composer [ https://substack.com/redirect/d1b6c6ad-b699-4f9d-accf-a145c37f36=
4d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] was=
 already the smart way to invest, and with its ChatGPT-4 integrations, it j=
ust got a lot smarter. Check it out for yourself, and as a Not Boring reade=
r, you can get an extra free week of Composer=E2=80=99s trial offering by e=
ntering =E2=80=9CNot Boring=E2=80=9D in the =E2=80=9CWhere did you hear abo=
ut us?=E2=80=9D section. This exclusive offer lasts until Friday 5/5 at 11:=
59pm EST, so check out Composer now:
(1) Not Boring: 200K Subscribers
Dan here =E2=80=94 Packy=E2=80=99s going to hate that I=E2=80=99m leading o=
ff with this self-promotional story. He=E2=80=99ll probably even demand tha=
t I remove it. But the cool thing about your boss also being your brother i=
s that you can sometimes tell him to fuck off.=20
Last Saturday Not Boring crossed 200,000 subscribers. That=E2=80=99s 3x the=
 amount of people that fit into Lincoln Financial Field, the home to our be=
loved Philadelphia Eagles. It=E2=80=99s a big milestone for Packy personall=
y, and also an important marker for Not Boring on our mission to make the w=
orld more optimistic. We=E2=80=99re starting to make a dent.
Packy=E2=80=99s been publicly quieter about the Not Boring journey over the=
 past year =E2=80=94 building in public isn=E2=80=99t always fun =E2=80=94 =
so I thought I=E2=80=99d share three observations about how he got here and=
 how he built Not Boring (with $0 in ad spend or pre-existing audience) int=
o one of the largest publications on Substack. These might seem like a bunc=
h of abstract cliches, but I=E2=80=99ll try to make them actionable:
Consistency: Packy publishes about 45 Monday essays per year. Each essay is=
 somewhere between 5,000 - 10,000 words. They=E2=80=99re a pain in the ass =
to write. Think about cramming out a 1,000 word essay on a late Sunday nigh=
t in your college library, but doing that basically every single week with =
200,000 professors waiting to grade it. Action: make a public promise, and =
follow through with it.
Quality: Packy=E2=80=99s standards for quality are exacting and sometimes f=
rustrating =E2=80=94 trust me, I=E2=80=99m his editor. He=E2=80=99ll write =
an essay for entire week, wake up Saturday morning, decide it=E2=80=99s shi=
t, and then spend the next 48 hours writing something entirely different. Q=
uality is the main driver of shareability, which is how our audience grows.=
 Action: put out work that you=E2=80=99re proud of and that people want to =
share.
Risk: When Packy started taking Not Boring seriously, he was unemployed, re=
cently married, and had a kid on the way. Not Boring had less than 1,000 su=
bscribers and made $0 in revenue. It=E2=80=99s not that he didn=E2=80=99t h=
ave other prospects =E2=80=94 he had built a solid career =E2=80=94 it=E2=
=80=99s that he was truly obsessed with writing about tech and strategy. Ac=
tion: everyone has their own risk:reward ratio, but if your goal is to acce=
lerate your success (in whatever it is that you do) you need to take some r=
isk.
If you want to learn more about Packy=E2=80=99s journey, this Acquired epis=
ode [ https://substack.com/redirect/17775eae-6a9b-4842-85cf-1f8aadaaca0e?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (filmed=
 right before 100K subscribers) is a good place to start. OK, that=E2=80=99=
s it for now. No more self-congratulations until a million subscribers =F0=
=9F=A4=9D.
Of course, none of this is possible without our smart, curious readers and =
subscribers. Thank you. Your support allows us to do what we love.
(2) Cruise robotaxis now run all day in San Francisco [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/9fbcfb48-7d73-4b46-8a8e-1eb44aab30ec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Frank Sinatra famously proclaimed that if you can =E2=80=9Cbuild self-drivi=
ng in SF, you can build it anywhere.=E2=80=9D Ole Blue Eyes was ahead of hi=
s time. And Cruise, the GM-owned self-driving company, is proving him right=
=2E
On Tuesday, Cruise founder and CEO Kyle Vogt tweeted that Cruise is now run=
ning 24/7 across San Francisco [ https://substack.com/redirect/a7e16877-8e3=
7-4e22-8411-addec4dd6857?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. During the day, Cruise employees and power-users will g=
et free access to the self-driving robotaxi and from 10pm-5:30am the servic=
e is open to paying customers in the general public. This is a big step in =
the broader commercial rollout of long-awaited self-driving taxis.
In his tweet, Vogt noted that building self-driving in SF has always been t=
he litmus test and hinted that that company will soon launch the service in=
 other markets.=20
The joke about self-driving cars is that they=E2=80=99re perpetually just a=
 few years away. Now that Cruise has pulled it off, joke=E2=80=99s on its d=
oubters.=20
(3) Brain Images Just Got 64 Million Times Sharper [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/bc84bb23-c4b1-47cd-953d-0fa6d0d931f3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Dan Vahaba [ https://substack.com/redirect/625688ed-80d0-49fb-90d1-25589e63=
d98b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] f=
or Duke Institute for Brain Sciences
The hope is that by making the MRI an even higher-powered microscope, Johns=
on and others can better understand mouse models of human diseases, such as=
 Huntington's disease, Alzheimer=E2=80=99s, and others. And that should lea=
d to a better understanding of how similar things function or go awry in pe=
ople.
A coalition of researchers, led by a team out of Duke, released MRI technol=
ogies that produce images 64 million times sharper than today=E2=80=99s sta=
ndard MRI imaging technology. The imagine technology uses incredibly powerf=
ul magnets, a special set of gradient coils, and the equivalent of 800 lapt=
ops=E2=80=99 worth computer power all to produce one brain image.=20
While the technology has only been tested on mice, the hope is that the enh=
anced brain imaging will enable doctors to better understand diseases like =
Parkinson=E2=80=99s, Alzheimer=E2=80=99s, and other neurodegenerative disea=
ses. Go Duke.=20
(4) Lego breaks ground on first US manufacturing facility [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/d544f32b-e124-416a-b736-0ca22b788158?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Sara Samora [ https://substack.com/redirect/c473ee85-ac37-498b-9dae-b9cac6c=
7b2c3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for Manufacturing Dive
The $1 billion, 1.7 million-square-foot site will house 13 buildings and dr=
aw its power from rooftop and ground solar panels, as well as an on-site so=
lar plant when completed in 2025.
Lego is opening up a new, $1B manufacturing facility about 15 miles outside=
 of Richmond, VA in a plan that will create about 1,700 new jobs. It=E2=80=
=99s Lego=E2=80=99s first US manufacturing facility, and will use on-site s=
olar to be carbon-neutral.=20
On a micro level: good for Lego and good for the city of Richmond!=20
On a macro level we expect to see this type of reshoring become more common=
 over the coming years. It=E2=80=99s not that every company needs to total =
scrap their international manufacturing efforts =E2=80=94 that=E2=80=99d be=
 an obvious overcorrection to the last few years =E2=80=94 but it can=E2=80=
=99t hurt to bring a portion of capacity back to the U.S. More jobs, more s=
table supply lines, and less dependency on China. Everything is awesome.=20
=E2=80=9CThe next big thing will start out looking like a toy manufacturer =
moving to the U.S. - Chris Dixon=E2=80=9D - Dan McCormick
(5) Immigration is back in the US [ https://substack.com/redirect/24aeefb7-=
d5e6-4718-8e00-760e3d5de677?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Rana Foroohar [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee0d31bf-41c8-4c55-8fbb-f780d=
b7e8748?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for FT
Immigration is back, in the US at least. Over the past two and a half years=
, immigration into the American labour market has increased by 4mn workers,=
 and the working age immigrant population has now finally reached its pre-p=
andemic trend level. This is likely to be a central factor in strong employ=
ment growth, particularly in leisure and hospitality. It is also part of th=
e story on increasing workforce participation, as well as being good news f=
or the fight against inflation.
Immigration, so hot right now. Immigration.
After a a multi-year period of immigration declines, due to Trump-era polic=
ies and the pandemic, immigration rates are back up. And the rise immigrati=
on is one of the driving forces keeping our economy afloat =E2=80=94 temper=
ing inflation, driving workforce participation, etc.
We often talk about the importance of high-skilled immigration to the U.S. =
because, frankly, that=E2=80=99s simply just a win-win for everybody. But t=
he recent rise in all kinds of immigration, and its positive impact on the =
economy is a reminder just how important it is to the stability of our econ=
omy. Immigrants (they get the job done!)
BONUS: Interactive Mutation Browser [ https://substack.com/redirect/e00b02f=
f-78fd-49b9-93b3-25dc393d9d90?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Not Boring Biotech Partner, Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/0e1691c5-0ff7-48aa-be26-497ce21bbb08?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], in The Century of Biology =20
From Elliot: With each ChatGPT update, more and more people are experiencin=
g the power of Large Language Models firsthand. But have you heard of Prote=
in Language Models? These new models are taking the biotech by storm. In pa=
rallel, scientists have developed fast and flexible 3D Web-based molecular =
graphics systems. The Interactive Mutation Browser weaves these two threads=
 together to explore the impact of genetic variants in real-time in the bro=
wser.
Even if you=E2=80=99re not a biologist, you should give it a spin: Interact=
ive Mutation Browser [ https://substack.com/redirect/c8edacc9-249b-4d52-a9c=
8-67068fd27976?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ]. It helps make an abstract concept like protein structure more tan=
gible. It=E2=80=99s cool to think that our kids are going to be able to lea=
rn using tools like this.=20
Book Rec: Anaximander [ https://substack.com/redirect/88ce2e70-9a97-45c5-aa=
15-760f4407db1c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] by Carlo Rovelli
This is the main characteristic of scientific thinking: what seems most obv=
ious to us about the world can be false. Scientific thinking is, therefore,=
 a continuous quest for novel ways of conceptualizing the world. Knowledge =
is born from a respectful but radical act of rebellion against what we curr=
ently think.=20
Packy here. I=E2=80=99m a simple man: Carlo Rovelli writes something, I rea=
d it.=20
The book is a celebration of Aximander, a 6th century BC Greek philosopher =
and, Rovelli argues, the world=E2=80=99s first scientist. It=E2=80=99s also=
 celebration of science as a rebellious act. What I loved most about the bo=
ok was Rovelli=E2=80=99s ability to put the creativity and boldness of Anax=
imander=E2=80=99s thinking in the context of his time. Seeking to explain t=
he world without deus ex deus =E2=80=94 explaining everything by saying =E2=
=80=9Cthe gods did it=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 was truly radical, and set the sta=
ge for 2600 years of scientific progress since.=20
How many of the universe=E2=80=99s secrets remain to be unveiled by shifts =
in perspective?
